  "opinion": "As a retired man from Los Angeles who migrated as a child and had a lower secondary education, I’ve watched generations of students struggle with the idea that they might not belong in science and technology fields. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory—it’s a real thing that makes people feel like they’re being judged before they even start. When kids hear things like 'girls aren’t good at math' or 'Black students don’t do well in engineering,' it affects their confidence. I remember my own experience growing up in a community where many people thought math was for boys only. That feeling of being unsure if you belong can be crushing. It’s not about labeling someone as weak; it’s about creating an environment where everyone feels safe to try. We should address it by making classrooms and labs more welcoming, where teachers openly talk about how everyone has the potential to succeed. In my time as a baker and photographer, I’ve seen how small changes—like encouraging students to share their ideas without fear—can make a big difference. The key is to build confidence from the start, not wait for someone to fall behind. It’s a challenge, but with patience and understanding, we can help students see themselves as capable in STEM. After all, every child deserves to believe they can contribute to the world through science and technology.",
